<Link id="l00397" /><CodeLine lineNumber="397"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00398" /><CodeLine lineNumber="398"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Splits the SCEV into two vectors of SCEVs representing the subscripts and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00399" /><CodeLine lineNumber="399"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// sizes of an array access. Returns the remainder of the delinearization that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00400" /><CodeLine lineNumber="400"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// is the offset start of the array.  The SCEV-&gt;delinearize algorithm computes</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00401" /><CodeLine lineNumber="401"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the multiples of SCEV coefficients: that is a pattern matching of sub</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00402" /><CodeLine lineNumber="402"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// expressions in the stride and base of a SCEV corresponding to the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00403" /><CodeLine lineNumber="403"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// computation of a GCD (greatest common divisor) of base and stride.  When</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00404" /><CodeLine lineNumber="404"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// SCEV-&gt;delinearize fails, it returns the SCEV unchanged.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00405" /><CodeLine lineNumber="405"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00406" /><CodeLine lineNumber="406"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// For example: when analyzing the memory access A&#91;i&#93;&#91;j&#93;&#91;k&#93; in this loop nest</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00407" /><CodeLine lineNumber="407"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00408" /><CodeLine lineNumber="408"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  void foo(long n, long m, long o, double A&#91;n&#93;&#91;m&#93;&#91;o&#93;) &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00409" /><CodeLine lineNumber="409"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00410" /><CodeLine lineNumber="410"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///    for (long i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00411" /><CodeLine lineNumber="411"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///      for (long j = 0; j &lt; m; j++)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00412" /><CodeLine lineNumber="412"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///        for (long k = 0; k &lt; o; k++)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00413" /><CodeLine lineNumber="413"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///          A&#91;i&#93;&#91;j&#93;&#91;k&#93; = 1.0;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00414" /><CodeLine lineNumber="414"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  &#125;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00415" /><CodeLine lineNumber="415"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00416" /><CodeLine lineNumber="416"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the delinearization input is the following AddRec SCEV:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00417" /><CodeLine lineNumber="417"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00418" /><CodeLine lineNumber="418"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  AddRec: &#123;&#123;&#123;%A,+,(8 &#42; %m &#42; %o)&#125;&lt;%for.i&gt;,+,(8 &#42; %o)&#125;&lt;%for.j&gt;,+,8&#125;&lt;%for.k&gt;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00419" /><CodeLine lineNumber="419"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00420" /><CodeLine lineNumber="420"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// From this SCEV, we are able to say that the base offset of the access is %A</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00421" /><CodeLine lineNumber="421"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// because it appears as an offset that does not divide any of the strides in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00422" /><CodeLine lineNumber="422"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the loops:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00423" /><CodeLine lineNumber="423"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00424" /><CodeLine lineNumber="424"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  CHECK: Base offset: %A</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00425" /><CodeLine lineNumber="425"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00426" /><CodeLine lineNumber="426"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// and then SCEV-&gt;delinearize determines the size of some of the dimensions of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00427" /><CodeLine lineNumber="427"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the array as these are the multiples by which the strides are happening:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="428"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="429"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  CHECK: ArrayDecl&#91;UnknownSize&#93;&#91;%m&#93;&#91;%o&#93; with elements of sizeof(double)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="430"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  bytes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00431" /><CodeLine lineNumber="431"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00432" /><CodeLine lineNumber="432"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Note that the outermost dimension remains of UnknownSize because there are</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00433" /><CodeLine lineNumber="433"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// no strides that would help identifying the size of the last dimension: when</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00434" /><CodeLine lineNumber="434"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// the array has been statically allocated, one could compute the size of that</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00435" /><CodeLine lineNumber="435"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// dimension by dividing the overall size of the array by the size of the known</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00436" /><CodeLine lineNumber="436"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// dimensions: %m &#42; %o &#42; 8</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00437" /><CodeLine lineNumber="437"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00438" /><CodeLine lineNumber="438"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Finally delinearize provides the access functions for the array reference</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00439" /><CodeLine lineNumber="439"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// that does correspond to A&#91;i&#93;&#91;j&#93;&#91;k&#93; of the above C testcase:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00440" /><CodeLine lineNumber="440"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00441" /><CodeLine lineNumber="441"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  CHECK: ArrayRef&#91;&#123;0,+,1&#125;&lt;%for.i&gt;&#93;&#91;&#123;0,+,1&#125;&lt;%for.j&gt;&#93;&#91;&#123;0,+,1&#125;&lt;%for.k&gt;&#93;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00442" /><CodeLine lineNumber="442"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00443" /><CodeLine lineNumber="443"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// The testcases are checking the output of a function pass:</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00447" /><CodeLine lineNumber="447" lineLink="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#abc378caf5071493fe3b2b98bf224be7c"><span class="doxyHighlightKeywordType">void</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#abc378caf5071493fe3b2b98bf224be7c">llvm::delinearize</a>(<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/scalarevolution">ScalarEvolution</a> &amp;SE, </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">const</span><span class="doxyHighlight"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/scev">SCEV</a> &#42;Expr,</span></CodeLine>
